@node Introduction "ToolTypeCopy Documentation - Introduction"

While I was rendering a RayTracing Icon for a program I was forced to use
third party software to convert the images to icons. After having some
icons converted I realised that there's no way to backup or store the
Tooltypes, often used to configure a program, in any sort or manner.
Reentering them by hand was the only way.

After the first frustration I started to hack a fast and easy sollution for
my problem, and voilą, here it is!

Created using SAS/C 6.56.

@endnode


@node Usage "ToolTypeCopy Documentation - Usage"

@{b}ToolTypeCopy@{ub} must only be used from the Shell. It does not
AmigaDOS ReadArgs()-Parsing because it's a hack!

1> ttc @{b}<from>@{ub} @{b}<to>@{ub}

@{i}Example:@{ui} ttc SYS:Prefs/IControl SYS:Prefs/Font

@{b}from@{ub} is the file you want to read the Tooltypes from; don't append
the '.info' suffix to this. Finally, @{b}to@{ub} is the file you want to
write the Tooltypes to; don't append the '.info' suffix to this either. Be
careful: the Tooltypes from the @{b}from@{ub}-file are taken without any other
actions or checks concerning the @{b}to@{ub}-file; the old tooltypes
of the @{b}to@{ub}-file are deleted.

@endnode


